Redescription. Body length is variable, between 16.2–21.7 mm in males and between 15.5–21.0 mm in females. The body is elongate, and varies from chestnut-brown to brown in color; the dorsal surface is glabrous and shiny; color variations exist, including tones from reddish to dark chestnut-brown, depending on the geographical area (Vallejo et. al. 1998 ). Pronotum (
Fig. 3
) is wider than it is long and slightly darker than the elytra. The head has minute punctures, especially on the vertex and the clypeus. The clypeus is short, trapezoidal with a concave anterior margin. Antennae (
Fig. 4
) are composed of 10 antennomeres, with long, defined antennal clubs. Protibia (
Fig. 5
) are flattened, slightly widened at their apical middle, shorter than the tarsomeres, with three dentate projections on the external margin, with a tibial spur. Tarsal claws (
Fig. 6
) are bifid, with two teeth in the apex. The male genital capsule (
Figs. 9–10
) has two symmetrical, short, rounded, slightly angular, laterally located The far aedeagus or internal sac has a sclerotized projection, extending beyond the general structure and sharpens into a thorn-like shape at the apex. Even though the female tarsal claws are not clearly as cleft as those of the males, they can be told apart from other sympatric species due to a rounded tubercle located very close to the apical margin of the pygidial plate (Morón 2006 ).
